<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About Jharkhand</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">Soul of <em>Vananchal</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">Jharkhand — literally "the land of forests" (jhar = forest, khand = land) — emerged as India's 28th state on November 15, 2000, carved from the southern half of Bihar after a century-long tribal struggle for self-determination. This is one of the most resource-rich pieces of land on earth: sitting atop vast reserves of coal, iron ore, copper, uranium, mica and dozens of other minerals that have fueled India's industrial economy for generations. Yet beneath these mineral riches lies a civilization far older and far more complex — the Adivasi (first peoples) of Jharkhand, whose tribes — Santali, Munda, Ho, Oraon, Kharia, Birhor and dozens more — have inhabited these Chota Nagpur Plateau forests since before recorded history. The Santali people gave the world one of the most extraordinary things in human linguistic history: the Ol Chiki script — an entirely original alphabet, created by scholar Pandit Raghunath Murmu in 1925, designed specifically for the Santali language's phonetics. It is one of the very few writing systems ever deliberately invented for a people who previously had none. Jharkhand's landscape is of extraordinary beauty: the Chota Nagpur Plateau — a billion-year-old Precambrian shield — covered in sal and mahua forests, scored by dozens of rivers tumbling over ancient granite in spectacular waterfalls. Hundru, Jonha, Dassam, Hirni and the roaring Lodh Falls are among the finest in India. The state's sacred geography — Deoghar's Baidyanath Jyotirlinga, Parasnath Hill (Sammed Shikharji), one of Jainism's holiest pilgrimage sites — draws millions of devotees annually. Jharkhand gave India Dhoni, Birsa Munda and a culture that celebrates the forest as mother, not resource.</p>
